Use the insights of the last two chunks and write two sentences about the type of precipitation variable. How useful is it?

Answer: The type of precipitation only discriminates between the two types rain and snow. Those two types mostly depend on the temperature, and will not influence the amount of precipitation. Because most extreme rainfalls occur in summer and snow is rare at the most stations all over the year, the result doesnât realy show any informations.

Load the anual overview on extreme rainfalls into a data.frame and plot a violine plot of the amount of extreme rainfalls per station.

#View(rain.annual)
ggplot(rain.annual, aes(factor(id), `extreme rainfall days`)) +
  geom_violin() + xlab("station id") + ylab("amount of extreme rainfall days whithin one year")

Redo the last exercise for the monthly extreme rainfall counts. Does this change the picture? What can you say about the distribution of extreme rainfall events from these plots?

#View(rain.monthly)
ggplot(rain.monthly, aes(factor(id), `extreme rainfall days`)) +
  geom_violin() + xlab("station id") + ylab("amount of extreme rainfall days whithin one month")

head(rain.monthly)

Answer: The plots are different. The amount of extreme rainfall days within one year is in average at least two times as high as the amount within one month. This means that the extreme rainfall events of the year never occured all in one month, even not in a two months time. I would state from this pictures, that the extreme rainfall events are distributet normal over the year.

Plot these locations and represent any measure for annual variance in extreme rainfall events by the point size of the used locations.
OPTIONAL: Additionally mark the station showing the most and least recorded extreme rainfalls by another marker into the same plot. (eg. use a green and a red cross or star.)

How can you interpret this result?

Answer: The stations with big variance in extreme rainfall events have had some years with many events and some with few. They therefore have a heterogenity over the years. The stations with little variance are affected by the extreme rainfall events mostly in the same amount, and as the colors show, have only had few rainfall events at all. Probably lots of extreme rainfall events are rare, but sometimes they occur. The rare occurence of years with lots of extreme rainfall events makes up the high variance. One might therefore expect a correlation between an increasing variance of yearly extreme rainfall events and the increasing overall amount of extreme rainfall events.
